emory usage in the Redis02 pod, which began at 18:11:00 CST. This was likely triggered by a surge in container-level memory consumption across multiple containers on the same host, possibly due to inefficient memory management or a memory leak in one or more applications. The memory pressure is corroborated by widespread anomalies in memory-related metrics, including JVM heap usage, OS memory utilization, and container memory limits being reached.\nMitigation Principles: Investigate application code and configuration in containers running on Redis02 for memory leaks, particularly around thread and connection handling.; Implement or enhance memory monitoring with alerts tuned to detect early signs of memory growth before limits are reached.; Review garbage collection logs and tune JVM settings if applicable to reduce memory pressure.; Enforce stricter memory limits and requests in Kubernetes to prevent noisy neighbors and enable earlier OOM termination under control.; Conduct regular load testing to simulate traffic patterns and validate memory behavior under stress.\n\nBackgroud:\n"\n\n\nBased on this information, identify the MOST LIKELY root cause component and reason from the candidate list.\nFollow these rules:\n- The root cause must be a single component from the candidate list.\n- The reason must be directly supported by the anomaly description.\n- Assign a suspicious score between 0.0 and 1.0 (higher = more confident).\n\nRespond ONLY with a JSON object in this exact format:\n{\n    "component": "service-name",\n    "reason": "brief reason",\n    "score": 0.92\n}'}]
